From d8ae5fa32c295361846665ec335c8d6b00b4b509 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Philippe Gerum <philippe.gerum@exail.com>
Date: Fri, 15 Mar 2024 15:37:39 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 150/171] net: dovetail: add infrastructure for oob device I/O

Enabling oob I/O for netdevices requires:

- the extension of the page pool implementation in order to enable oob
  access to dedicated pool of pages for buffer allocation and release
  (PP_FLAG_PAGE_OOB). This simplifies the addition of oob support to
  the netdevice drivers already using page pools for allocating their
  buffers (e.g. XDP-enabled drivers normally do).

- a significant rework of the Dovetail-specific skbuff handling in
  order to support proper recycling by the companion core, depending
  on the stage buffers are released from, and which among the in-band
  or oob netstacks actually owns them. The gist of the changes is
  about decoupling the information about the stage which owns the
  buffer head (skb->oob_head set if oob) from the information about
  the stage which owns the storage the buffer meta-data refers to
  (skb_shinfo(skb)->flags & SKBFL_OOB_STORAGE is non-zero if the
  storage lives in an oob-enabled page pool).

- the introduction of a global pool of buffer heads which may be
  accessed from the oob stage for allocation and release.

- making __build_skb() aware of the existence of the oob buffer pool,
  so that a new head from the latter when the caller runs oob, which
  eventually makes this routine oob-capable.

- teaching a critical portion of the NAPI how to deal with the
  out-of-band execution stage, so that fewer changes to NIC drivers
  are required for enabling oob traffic.

Signed-off-by: Philippe Gerum <philippe.gerum@exail.com>
